<paragraph blockId="17.[167,776,985,1316]" pageId="17" pageNumber="668">
<emphasis box="[168,774,985,1009]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="668" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[168,327,985,1009]" pageId="17" pageNumber="668">Identification.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[338,554,985,1009]" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Anthurium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" pageId="17" pageNumber="668" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pirrense">
<emphasis box="[338,554,985,1009]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="668">Anthurium pirrense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished by
</emphasis>
its epiphytic habit, short stems with persistent and fibrous cataphylls, subterete petioles, oblong-elliptic and subcoriaceous blades with the collective vein relatively separated from the margin. Also characteristic is its slender yellowish-brown spadices and the violet rings around the pistils. It can be confused with the sympatric 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="668">
<collectionCode box="[653,673,1190,1213]" country="USA" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15406" name="Harvard University - Arnold Arboretum" pageId="17" pageNumber="668" type="Herbarium">A</collectionCode>
. crassite- palum
</emphasis>
, but this species comprises thinner blades (when dry) and yellowish-green spadices with a cobbled appearance due to its thickened and elevated tepals.
</paragraph>
